  <h1>Teaching</h1>
  
  <section id="philosophy">
    <h2 class="section-title">Teaching Philosophy</h2>
    <p>
      My teaching approach draws from both Western pedagogical traditions and Indian educational philosophies, 
      particularly the Guru-Shishya parampara and experiential learning emphasized in ancient Indian texts. 
      I believe that true understanding comes not just from theoretical knowledge, but from hands-on practice, 
      reflection, and dialogue.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      In my courses, I emphasize:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Experiential Learning:</strong> Learning by doing through projects, labs, and real-world applications</li>
      <li><strong>Cultural Context:</strong> Understanding technology within its cultural and historical context</li>
      <li><strong>Interdisciplinarity:</strong> Bridging computer science, linguistics, philosophy, and traditional knowledge systems</li>
      <li><strong>Ethical Awareness:</strong> Critical reflection on the societal impacts of AI and technology</li>
      <li><strong>Collaborative Discovery:</strong> Learning as a shared journey between teacher and students</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="quote-box">
      <p class="sanskrit">श्रुत्वा अपि बहुशः श्रावयत्यश्रुतम् उत्तमोत्तमम्</p>
      <p class="quote-translation">
        "Even having heard many times, the excellent teacher makes one hear as if unheard" 
        - Emphasizing fresh perspective and continuous discovery
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="current-courses">
    <h2 class="section-title">Current Courses</h2>

    <div class="course">
      <h3>AI for Indian Knowledge Systems</h3>
      <div class="course-meta">
        <span>Graduate Level</span> • <span>15 weeks</span> • <span>Fall 2024</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        This course explores how artificial intelligence can be used to preserve, analyze, and extend 
        Indian Knowledge Systems. Students learn NLP techniques for Indian languages, knowledge representation 
        for traditional texts, and ethical considerations in digitizing indigenous knowledge.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Topics Covered:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Introduction to Indian Knowledge Systems (Ayurveda, Jyotisha, Vyakarana, etc.)</li>
        <li>Challenges in Indian language NLP (morphology, sandhi, diglossia)</li>
        <li>OCR for historical scripts and manuscripts</li>
        <li>Knowledge graphs and ontologies for traditional knowledge</li>
        <li>Ethical issues: ownership, access, and misappropriation</li>
        <li>Case studies: Digitizing palm leaf manuscripts, Sanskrit parsing, Ayurvedic text mining</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Projects:</strong> Students build AI systems for a specific IKS domain of their choice.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="course">
      <h3>Generative AI and Indic Systems</h3>
      <div class="course-meta">
        <span>Graduate/Advanced Undergraduate</span> • <span>12 weeks</span> • <span>Spring 2024</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A hands-on course on generative AI technologies (LLMs, diffusion models, etc.) with a focus on 
        applications to Indian languages, arts, and cultural contexts. Students learn to fine-tune models, 
        work with multilingual data, and create culturally-grounded generative applications.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Topics Covered:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Foundations of transformer architectures and attention mechanisms</li>
        <li>Fine-tuning LLMs for low-resource Indian languages</li>
        <li>Prompt engineering and in-context learning</li>
        <li>Generative models for Indian art, music, and poetry</li>
        <li>Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) for Indian texts</li>
        <li>Evaluation and bias in multilingual models</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Projects:</strong> Build a generative application for an Indic language or cultural domain.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="course">
      <h3>Machine Learning Foundations</h3>
      <div class="course-meta">
        <span>Undergraduate</span> • <span>14 weeks</span> • <span>Fall 2024</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A comprehensive introduction to machine learning covering supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement 
        learning. The course uses examples from Indian contexts throughout, making the material more relatable 
        for students.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Topics Covered:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Linear models, decision trees, and neural networks</li>
        <li>Classification, regression, and clustering</li>
        <li>Feature engineering and model evaluation</li>
        <li>Introduction to deep learning and CNNs</li>
        <li>Ethics and fairness in ML</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Unique Approach:</strong> Examples drawn from Indian agriculture, healthcare, languages, and social contexts.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="course">
      <h3>Natural Language Processing for Indic Languages</h3>
      <div class="course-meta">
        <span>Graduate Level</span> • <span>Workshop Series</span> • <span>Offered Annually</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        An intensive workshop series on NLP specifically for Indian languages. Covers both foundational 
        techniques and state-of-the-art methods, with emphasis on handling the unique characteristics 
        of Indian language families.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Topics Covered:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Linguistic characteristics of Indian languages (Dravidian, Indo-Aryan, Tibeto-Burman)</li>
        <li>Tokenization, morphological analysis, and POS tagging</li>
        <li>Multilingual embeddings and cross-lingual transfer</li>
        <li>Machine translation for Indian language pairs</li>
        <li>Low-resource NLP techniques</li>
        <li>Building and using Indic corpora</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

